The subject containing a term not in the nominative is next examined and expounded. The rule is that the genitive (or other case not the nominative) becomes universal in the second or negative exponent, v. g. ‘Every A of any Β is C Some A of some Β is C, and no A of any B is not C) This Wyclif proves by analysis of the proposition. There are, however, cases when this is not true: as ‘Every servant obedient to lzis master is liked by you. Or ‘He is the master of an obedient servant.³ If the genitive precede the nomi- native, then the term that comes first is alone universal.

I must here correct a foot-note on p. 93 that was not suffi- ciently considered. Wyclif (l. 37) points out that this proposition is false: eEvery proposition or its contradictory is true3' the reason is that ‘Every proposition' comprises contradictor-ies too; so the opposition implied by or cannot be posited.
